e surface of the ice sheet to 40% of the calculated melt total (red lines).Extended Data Fig. 4 Sliding-dependence of the entropy signature.Local Shannon entropy (LSE) values calculated from mass loss components using a range of basal traction values (phi = [5, 15, 25]) for climate warming scenarios of a, 8 and b, 12° C, and c, d duplicates but with a baseline climate 4° C warming that the reference scenarios. Lower phi facilitates greater basal sliding across the domain, wherever thermal conditions permit. Generally, phi = 5 leads to sliding everywhere, whereas phi = 25 prevents sliding. The default phi = 15 allows a balanced scenario in which sliding arises in fast-flowing outlets around the ice sheet margin, comparable to the modern East Antarctic Ice Sheet. Semi-transparent lines show the 10-year resolution outputs, bold lines show running mean.Extended Data Fig. 5 Model state-dependence of the entropy signature.Local Shannon entropy (LSE) values calculated from mass loss components from three 500000 year runs that use oscillatory forcings but a constant (rather than warming) baseline climate. LSE values under the coldest climate state, coupled with weak ocean forcing (blue lines), are considerably lower than under the intermediate climate state with medium ocean forcing strength (yellow lines). The simulation under a constant warm atmosphere with strong ocean forcing (red lines) shows LSE values lower than the intermediate state and dropping to very low values under peak warmth conditions. The arched structures visible especially in intermediate and warm experiments reflect the fewer data points (and hence reduced potential for variability, leading to greater predictability) within the sliding entropy calculation window at the beginning and end of the simulation. Semi-transparent lines show the 10-year resolution outputs, bold lines show running mean.Extended Data Fig. 6 Temperature sensitivity of floating ice.a, Proportion of total ice area represented by grounded and floating fractions as a function of temperature anomaly. These are approximately equal at low temperatures, but are strongly skewed at warmer temperatures. At the warmest end of the simulation, floating ice accounts for only 6.9% of total ice area. b, Ice-shelf area as a function of temperature anomaly. At low temperatures (below delta_T = -2K) ice shelves are more extensive during a climate trajectory of warming (brown) than during cooling (blue), most likely due to the retreat of grounded ice. In the intermediate state (-2K < delta_T < 4K) ice-shelf extent at a given temperature is typically greater during cooling than warming, but the relationship is highly variable. This is the regime of bistability identified in Fig. 2e–g. Above approximately delta_T = 4K, ice-shelf extent is minimal, but consistent between warming and cooling trajectories. Vertical lines in both panels identify approximate temperature anomaly thresholds of behavioural regimes observed in Fig. 2b–d.Supplementary informationSupplementary Information (download PDF )Supplementary Discussion and Figs. 1–3.Peer Review File (download PDF )Rights and permissionsSpringer Nature or its licensor (e.g. a society or other partner) holds exclusive rights to this article under a publishing agreement with the author(s) or other rightsholder(s); author self-archiving of the accepted manuscript version of this article is solely governed by the terms of such publishing agreement and applicable law.Reprints and permissionsAbout this articleCite this articleGolledge, N.R., Naish, T.R., Lowry, D.P. et al. Ice-sheet regime shifts with climate warming.
